04723nam a22007935i 9789048513208DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485132087 a10.1515/97890485132082doi  a(DE-B1597)517627  a(OCoLC)1083583517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a751.730939181 aMoormann, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivine Interiors :bMural Paintings in Greek and Roman Sanctuaries /cEric Moormann. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (268 p.) :b32 color plates, 100 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmsterdam Archaeological Studies ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Paintings Described in Ancient Texts -- t2. Paintings Found in Public Temples of the Greek world -- t3. Paintings Found in Public Temples in Roman Italy -- t4. Paintings in Provincial Roman Temples Across the Alps -- t5. The Eastern Half of the Empire and North Africa -- t6. Painted Shrines Dedicated to the Roman Emperor -- t7. Roman Shrines Housing Non-Roman Cults -- t8. Dura Europos: A Case Study -- t9. Final Remarks -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Textual Sources -- tIndex of Names, Places and Subjects -- tColour plates0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMighty marble facades, sculptures, and wall paintings played an important role in the decoration of Greek and Roman temples. While the official temples, which were connected with a city or a state, usually had a simple but solemn appearance, the more popular buildings were true multi-colored expressions of religiosity. Scenes from the life of the revered deity, portraits of the supporters and practitioners of the cult, and renderings of plants and animals could transport visitors to these shrines to different worlds. The wall paintings displayed differences in style and taste, but they had the same basic look everywhere. It is striking to see the similarities between temples that were widely separated in the vast Greco-Roman world. Drawing on archaeological remains and texts of antiquity, Divine Interiors fills a void in Greek and Roman studies by exploring a large variety of decorative schemes and fashions all over the ancient world and by shedding light on the devotional practices of worshippers and the use of shrines and temples in daily life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt and religionzGreece. 0aArt and religionzRome. 0aTempleszGreece. 0aTemples, Roman. 4aARC. 4aAntiquity. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066278840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048513208zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048513208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048513208.jpg  a978-3-11-060651-5  AUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8  Amsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2002d2015  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK